Prototype chain

When we try to access a property on an object,JS first looks inside the object.
If not found → it looks in its prototype → then prototype’s prototype → and so on.
This lookup process is called the prototype chain.

every js object has a hidden property

user → user.__proto__ → Object.prototype → null
example-->const arr = [1, 2, 3];
arr → Array.prototype → Object.prototype → null

In JavaScript, arrays, strings, and functions are all objects
But they are special types of objects

arr → Array.prototype → Object.prototype → null  ---> array
greet → Function.prototype → Object.prototype → null---->function

Auto-boxing = JavaScript automatically converts a primitive into an object temporarily when you try to use methods on it.


Constructor Function
A constructor function is a normal function used to create multiple objects with the same structure (template/blueprint).
example
function Person(name, age) {
  this.name = name;
  this.age = age;
}

const p1 = new Person("Agraj", 22);
const p2 = new Person("Rahul", 25);

Role of new Keyword
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

const p1 = Person("Agraj"); // ❌
this will point to:
window (non-strict)
undefined (strict mode)
 So always use new

 | Feature           | Constructor Function    | Factory Function |
| ----------------- | ----------------------- | ---------------- |
| `new` keyword     | Required                | Not required     |
| `this` usage      | Yes                     | No               |
| Return value      | Automatic               | Manual           |
| Prototype         | Yes                     | No (by default)  |
| Memory efficiency | Better (shared methods) | Can be worse     |
| Simplicity        | Medium                  | Easy             |


this in JavaScript

this is used to refer to the current object that is executing the function.
👉 In simple words:
this helps you access and manipulate data of the object you're working with

use of this --->
Avoid hardcoding object names
 Enable reusability
 Provide dynamic context
example---->
 const user = {
  name: "Agraj",
  greet() {
    console.log(this.name);
  }
};

const fn = user.greet;
fn(); // undefined ❌

A function was originally part of an object,
 but when you call it separately, it no longer knows which object it belongs to
So this becomes wrong (or undefined).

